        <div xml:id="AN12-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN12">
            <lg type="edition"><l>yāyē, kaṇṇiṉuṅ kaṭuṅkā talaḷē yentaiyu</l>
<l>nilaṉuṟap <choice><seg>poṟāac</seg><seg>peṟāac</seg></choice> cīṟaṭi civappa</l>
<l>vevaṉila kuṟumaka ḷiyaṅkuti yeṉṉum</l>
<l>yāmē, <choice><seg>piriviṉ</seg><seg>tuṇiviṉ</seg></choice> ṟiyainta tuvarā naṭpi</l>
<l>ṉirutalaip puḷḷi ṉōruyi rammē</l>
<l>yēṉalaṅ <choice><seg>kāva<supplied>la</supplied></seg><seg>kāvala</seg></choice> rāṉā tārttoṟuṅ</l>
<l>kiḷiviḷi payiṟṟum veḷilāṭu peruñciṉai</l>
<l>viḻukkōṭ palaviṉ <choice><seg>paḻū<supplied>u</supplied>ppayaṉ</seg><seg>paḻūuppayaṅ</seg></choice> koṇmār</l>
<l>kuṟava rūṉṟiya kurampai putaiya</l>
<l>vēṅkai <choice><seg>tāya</seg><seg>pāya</seg></choice> tēmpāy tōṟṟam</l>
<l>pulicettu verīiya pukarmuka vēḻa</l>
<l>maḻaipaṭu <choice><seg><supplied>ci</supplied>lampiṟ</seg><seg>cilampiṟ</seg></choice> kaḻaipaṭap peyaru</l>
<l>nalvarai nāṭa nīvariṉ</l>
<l>melliya lōrun tāṉvā ḻalaḷē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>My mother, she has love [for her] fiercer than [for her] eye and my father</l>
<l>says: “eh, why would you stir, little girl</l>
<l rend="indent">	for [your] little feet to become red that do not bear to touch the ground?”</l>
<l>We, in undivided intimacy, enjoyable without separation,</l>
<l>we are of one life, like a bird with two heads.</l>
<l>Oh man from a land of good mountains,</l>
<l>where the elephant bull with spotted face, frightened when thinking of the tiger</l>
<l rend="indent">	at the honey-shedding appearance of the kino tree when it spreads [in bloom],</l>
<l rend="indent">	so that the huts are buried that were fixed by the hill people</l>
<l rend="indent">	in order to take the ripening yield of the jack tree with excellent [fruit] bunches</l>
<l rend="indent">	on big branches where squirrels play that repeat parakeets sounds,</l>
<l>moves, for the bamboo to fall, on the rainy mountain side,</l>
<l>whenever the millet guards make [their] unending roar,</l>
<l rend="indent">	if you come</l>
<l>she with soft nature for one, too,<note place="foot">ōrum is a problem here and unsurprisingly glossed as acai by the old commentary.  Alternatively it could be taken as the peyareccam of ōrtal: “she with soft nature, when she perceives [it], will not live”.</note> will not live.</l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
